Sure, I'd be happy to help you understand how to construct and code a breadth-first search (BFS) algorithm in C++.

Breadth first search (BFS) is one of the easiest algorithms for searching a graph. It also serves as a prototype for several other important graph algorithms that we will study later. Here's how to do it:

```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <list>

using namespace std;

class Graph {
    int V; 
    list<int> *adj;

public:
    Graph(int V);

    void addEdge(int v, int w);

    void BFS(int s);
};

Graph::Graph(int V) {
    this->V = V;
    adj = new list<int>[V];
}

void Graph::addEdge(int v, int w) {
    adj[v].push_back(w);
}

void Graph::BFS(int s) {
    bool *visited = new bool[V];
    for(int i = 0; i < V; i++)
        visited[i] = false;

    list<int> queue;

    visited[s] = true;
    queue.push_back(s);

    while(!queue.empty()) {
        s = queue.front();
        cout << s << " ";
        queue.pop_front();

        for (auto i = adj[s].begin(); i != adj[s].end(); ++i) {
            if (!visited[*i]) {
                queue.push_back(*i);
                visited[*i] = true;
            }
        }
    }
}
```
Here is the explanation:
1. We maintain a boolean array visited[] to track the vertices that have been visited since a BFS starts from an arbitrary vertex.
2. We store each vertex in a queue and then at each step, popping it off to visit neighbors that haven't been visited yet, marking them as visited and pushing them into the queue.
3. When queue becomes empty, BFS has visited every vertex in the connected component, and it will halt.

In the main() function, create a Graph, add edges and then call the BFS traversal.
```c++
int main() {
    Graph g(4);
    g.addEdge(0, 1);
    g.addEdge(0, 2);
    g.addEdge(1, 2);
    g.addEdge(2, 0);
    g.addEdge(2, 3);
    g.addEdge(3, 3);

    cout << "Breadth First Traversal (start vertex 2) ";
    g.BFS(2);

    return 0;
}
```

Remember, this implementation is for unweighted graphs, which means the distance between all edges is equal. If it were a weighted graph, a priority queue would be needed instead of a queue to select the next most promising vertex to visit.

