Here is a solution written in Java.

```java
import java.util.*;
import java.lang.*;

class Solution {
    public String stringXor(String a, String b) {
        StringBuilder xor = new StringBuilder();

        // Calculate the length of strings 
        int a_len = a.length();
        int b_len = b.length();

        // Make both strings of equal lengths by adding preceding 0's in the smaller string. 
        // Here, assume that length(a) > length(b).
        while(a_len < b_len) {
            a = "0" + a;
            a_len++;
        }

        while(b_len < a_len) {
            b = "0" + b;
            b_len++;
        }

        // Finding xor and forming new string
        for(int i = 0; i < a_len; i++) {
            // If the character bits are same (both 0's or 1's), then take '0'
            if(a.charAt(i) == b.charAt(i)) {
                xor.append('0');
            }
            // If the character bits are different (one 0 and one 1), then take '1'
            else {
                xor.append('1');
            }
        }

        return xor.toString();
    }
}
```

The `stringXor` function first determines the length of both the input strings. If the strings are not the same length, preceding 0's are added to the smaller string until both strings are the same length. Then it goes bit by bit through each string, performing an XOR operation on each corresponding bit in the strings. This xor value is then appended to a new string which is returned.

