Yes, Java 8 introduced `Comparator.nullsFirst` and `Comparator.nullsLast` methods to cater exactly to this need. Here's an example which does exactly what you need:

```Java
private static class BarComparator implements Comparator<Foo> {
    public int compare(final Foo o1, final Foo o2) {
        return Comparator.comparing(Foo::getBar, Comparator.nullsFirst(String::compareTo)).compare(o1, o2);
    }
}
```

Please note that `Foo` must have a `getBar` method to get the value of `bar`.

Here's how it works:

- `Comparator.comparing(Foo::getBar, Comparator.nullsFirst(String::compareTo))` returns a comparator that compares two `Foo` objects by the value of their `bar` attributes. It uses `String::compareTo` method to do the comparison, hence `bar` attributes must be of `String` type or any type that implements `Comparable`. In case `bar` of any `Foo` object is `null`, `Comparator.nullsFirst` ensures that `null`s are considered less than non-null values. If you would like `null`s to be considered greater than non-null values, you could use `Comparator.nullsLast` in place of `Comparator.nullsFirst`.

- `.compare(o1, o2)` method then uses this comparator to compare `o1` and `o2` and return the comparison result.

This does exactly the same thing as doing a bunch of `if`...`else` checks to compare `o1` and `o2`, handling all possibilities of `o1`, `o2`, `o1.bar`, `o2.bar` being `null`. But it keeps the code clear and concise.

