```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
#include <atomic>

std::atomic<int> totalSum(0);

// Function to calculate sum in each thread
void calculateSum(int start, int end) {
    int partialSum = 0;
    for (int i = start; i <= end; ++i) {
        partialSum += i;
    }
    totalSum += partialSum;

    std::cout << "Partial sum from "<< start << " to "<< end << " = "<< partialSum<<'\n';
}

int main() {
    int N, M;

    std::cout << "Enter integer N: ";
    std::cin >> N;

    std::cout << "Enter integer M: ";
    std::cin>> M;

    // array to hold all thread objects
    std::thread threads[M]; 

    int batchSize = N / M;
    int start = 1;

    for (int i = 0; i < M; ++i) {
        int end = start + batchSize - 1;
        if (i == M - 1) { //if last thread, should calculate till N
            end = N;
        }
        threads[i] = std::thread(calculateSum, start, end); 
        start = end + 1; // update the start for next thread
    }

    // Join all threads
    for (int i = 0; i < M; ++i) {
        threads[i].join();
    }

    std::cout << "Total Sum = " << totalSum << '\n';

    return 0;
}
```

Note: Just be aware that depending on the system and the value of N, increasing M can actually decrease performance due to overhead associated with creating and managing threads, as well as potential contention for shared resources.

This C++ program works by creating M worker threads, and assigning each thread a range of integers to sum. The threads then perform their computation concurrently, update an atomic variable `totalSum` with their partial sum, and terminate. This gives us a time complexity of approximately O(N/M), assuming no contention for shared resources, and a space complexity of O(M) for holding the thread objects. 

The atomic variable `totalSum` is used to prevent a race condition between the threads when updating the shared total sum variable.

