```Java
public Node addTwoLists(Node headA, Node headB) {
    Node dummyNode = new Node(0);
    Node current = dummyNode;
    int carry = 0;

    while(headA != null || headB != null){
        int x = (headA != null) ? headA.data : 0;
        int y = (headB != null) ? headB.data : 0;
        int sum = carry + x + y;
        carry = sum/10;

        current.adjacent = new Node(sum % 10);
        current = current.adjacent;

        if (headA != null) headA = headA.adjacent;
        if (headB != null) headB = headB.adjacent;
    }
    if(carry > 0){
        current.adjacent = new Node(carry);
    }

    return dummyNode.adjacent;
}

class Node {
    int data;
    Node adjacent;
    Node(int d) {
        data = d;
        adjacent = null;
    }
}
```

The addTwoLists method starts by creating a new "dummy" node and a "current" pointer pointing at the dummy node. Then, it enters a loop which continues until both of input lists have been completely traversed.

