Below is an implementation using Java's Concurrency API, specifically `ForkJoinPool` and `RecursiveTask` for a divide-and-conquer approach to the maximum subarray problem. This approach breaks down the problem into smaller, more manageable tasks that can be solved concurrently. However, since this is a recursive approach, it comes with memory usage and time execution trade-offs.

```java
import java.util.concurrent.ForkJoinPool;
import java.util.concurrent.RecursiveTask;

public class MaxSubarray {

    private static class MaxSubarrayTask extends RecursiveTask<int[]> {
        private final int[] nums;
        private final int low;
        private final int high;

        public MaxSubarrayTask(int[] nums, int low, int high) {
            this.nums = nums;
            this.low = low;
            this.high = high;
        }

        @Override
        protected int[] compute() {
            if (high == low) {
                return new int[] {low, high, nums[low]};
            } else {
                int mid = (low + high) >>> 1;

                MaxSubarrayTask leftTask = new MaxSubarrayTask(nums, low, mid);
                MaxSubarrayTask rightTask = new MaxSubarrayTask(nums, mid+1, high);

                invokeAll(leftTask, rightTask);

                int[] leftSubarray = leftTask.join();
                int[] rightSubarray = rightTask.join();
                int[] crossSubarray = findMaxCrossingSubarray(nums, low, mid, high);

                if (leftSubarray[2] >= rightSubarray[2] && leftSubarray[2] >= crossSubarray[2]) {
                    return leftSubarray;
                } else if (rightSubarray[2] >= leftSubarray[2] && rightSubarray[2] >= crossSubarray[2]) {
                    return rightSubarray;
                } else {
                    return crossSubarray;
                }
            }
        }

        private int[] findMaxCrossingSubarray(int[] nums, int low, int mid, int high) {
            int leftSum = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
            int sum = 0;
            int maxLeft = mid;

            for (int i = mid; i >= low; i--) {
                sum = sum + nums[i];
                if (sum > leftSum) {
                    leftSum = sum;
                    maxLeft = i;
                }
            }

            int rightSum = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
            sum = 0;
            int maxRight = mid;

            for (int j = mid+1; j <= high; j++) {
                sum = sum + nums[j];
                if (sum > rightSum) {
                    rightSum = sum;
                    maxRight = j;
                }
            }

            return new int[] {maxLeft, maxRight, leftSum + rightSum};
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] nums = {-2, -5, 6, -2, -3, 1, 5, -6};

        ForkJoinPool pool = ForkJoinPool.commonPool();
        MaxSubarrayTask task = new MaxSubarrayTask(nums, 0, nums.length-1);

        int[] result = pool.invoke(task);

        System.out.println("Maximum subarray starts at index " + result[0] +
                           ", ends at index " + result[1] +
                           ", and its sum is " + result[2]);
    }
}
``` 

An important note is that divide-and-conquer approach to this problem achieves the time complexity of O(n log n), which is worse than O(n) achieved by Kadanes algorithm doing this in a single pass through the array. The divide-and-conquer technique chosen here is specifically to illustrate how Java's Concurrency API can be leveraged to implement a multithreaded solution. And, this solution will have better performance with very large arrays on systems with a high degree of parallelism.
